Java Beginner Guide

1. Java Basics
•	Terminologies – Understanding key terms like programming Languages
•	Hello World Program – Writing and running your first Java program.
•	JDK, JRE, JVM and Behind the Scenes – How Java works internally.
•	Oracle Coding Style – Best practices for naming and formatting code.
•	Comments – Single-line (//) and multi-line (/* ... */) comments.

2. Variables, Data Types & Operators

•	Variables – Declaring and initializing variables.
•	DataTypes – Primitive and reference types.
•	Numbers: int, long, float, double
•	Character: char
•	Boolean: boolean
•	String – Immutable sequences of characters.
•	Binary Number – Representing binary literals.
•	Primitive and Reference Data Types – Differences and usage.
•	Final Variables – Constants in Java.
•	Type Casting – Widening vs narrowing conversions.
•	Arithmetic Operators – +, -, *, /, %.
•	Relational Operators – <, >, <=, >=, ==, !=.
•	Logical Operators – &&, ||, !.
•	Boolean Expressions – True/false evaluation.
•	Ternary Operator – condition ? value1 : value2.
•	Comparison of == and equals() – Reference vs value equality.

3. Control Flow

•	Conditional Statements – if, if-else, if-else-if.
•	Switch Statements – Multi-branch selection.
•	Looping Statements – for, enhanced for (for-each).
•	while and do-while loops.
•	Break and Continue Statements – Controlling loop flow.

4. Methods

•	Methods – Defining reusable code blocks.
•	Main Method – Entry point of a Java application.
•	Calling Methods – Invoking methods with arguments.
•	VarArgs – Variable length arguments.
•	Method Overloading – Same method name, different parameter list.
•	Static Methods – Class-level methods.
•	Instance Methods – Instance Level Methods

5. Arrays & Collections Basics

•	Arrays – One-dimensional arrays.
•	Multidimensional Arrays – 2D and higher arrays.
•	Array Exceptions – ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException.
•	String and Character Arrays – Conversions between String, char[], and String[].

6. Object-Oriented Programming

•	Introduction to OOP – Classes, objects, and principles.
•	Package – Organizing classes.
•	Constructors – Initializing objects.
•	Constructor Overloading – Multiple constructors in a class.
•	this Keyword – Referring to the current object.
•	Access Modifiers – public, private, protected, default.
•	Encapsulation – Hiding data using getters and setters.
•	Inheritance – Extending classes.
•	Protected Modifier – Access in subclasses and same package.
•	super Keyword – Accessing superclass members.
•	Objects of Subclass – Using child class instances.
•	Method Overriding – Redefining methods in subclasses.
•	Polymorphism – Runtime and compile-time behavior.
•	Abstraction – Abstract classes and interfaces.
•	Annotation – Metadata in Java.
•	Enums – Enum types for fixed constants.
•	Objects and their Properties – State and behavior.

7. Exception Handling

•	Errors and Exceptions – Difference between compile-time and runtime errors.
•	Hierarchy of Exceptions – Checked, unchecked, and errors.
•	NullPointerException – Common causes and fixes.

8. Strings & Formatting

•	StringBuilder – Mutable string operations.
•	Formatted Outputs – System.out.printf(), String.format().
